\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
(First proof): The quotient-map-followed-by-isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}:\Z_{p}\to\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

 is a compatible family of maps to the limitands of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

, giving a unique map 
\begin_inset Formula $q:\Z_{p}\to\lim\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|_{p}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, so there is some power of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}(x)\neq0\in\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 has trivial kernel, and is thus injective.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

 actually is the limit, we must show that maps into the limitands from an
 auxillary object factor uniquely through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be auxillary, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}:Z\to\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

 be a family of compatible maps.
 Exploit the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z_{p}/p^{n}\Z_{p}\approx\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

 to a pick, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\Z$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}+p^{n}\Z_{p}=f_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Compatibility of the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=x_{n}\mod p^{n}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is cauchy 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adically, thus convergent.
 We then define 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=\lim_{n}x_{n}:Z\to\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Check compatibility: 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{n}\circ f)(z)=\lim x_{n}+p^{n}\Z_{p}=x_{n}+p^{n}\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{n+1,n}\circ f_{n+1})(z)=x_{n+1}+p^{n}\Z=x_{n}+p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

.
