\begin_layout Itemize
(Second proof): First note that a countable product of complete metric spaces
 is complete metrizable.
 For metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(,):X_{i}\times X_{i}\to\R_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

, we can reduce to the case where each 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 is bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 by transforming 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\left(,\right)\mapsto\frac{d_{i}\left(,\right)}{d_{i}\left(,\right)+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the metric on the product will be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\{x_{i}\},\{y_{i}\})=\sum_{i}\frac{d_{i}(x_{i},y_{i})}{2^{i}}$
\end_inset

 which is again bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 To prove gives the product topology, note that for any collection of open
 balls for which all but finitely many are the whole space 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, the rapid decay of the contribution to the metric causes effectively no
 contribution from those all but finitely many sapces, so any open in the
 product will be contained in a metric open.
 Conversely, any metric open will contain a product open for similar reasons.
 Completness comes reasonably: the metric on the product dominates the metric
 on the factors.
 Thus a cauchy sequence in the product demands a cauchy sequence in the
 factors.
 The factors are complete, so the components converge.
 The product of the limits is the limit of the product.
 Specify this general result to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z_{p}$
\end_inset

 by using the discrete metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}(,)$
\end_inset

.
 Then define 
\begin_inset Formula $d(,)$
\end_inset

 on the product as before, but instead of summing over inverse powers of
 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, use 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

 is a compatible subspace of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

.
 Compatibility demands for 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}\neq\{y_{i}\}$
\end_inset

, a smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=y_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\leq N$
\end_inset

 and not equal otherwise.
 Then compute the distance between two sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\{x_{n}\},\{y_{n}\})=\sum_{n\mbox{ up to }N}p^{-n}\cdot0+\sum_{\mbox{the rest}}p^{-n}\cdot1=\frac{p^{-(N+1)}}{1-1/p}=p^{-N}\frac{1}{p-1}.$
\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{n}\},\{y_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 actually come from honest integers 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\sim|x-y|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Now all we need to show is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Z$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\Z/p^{n}\Z$
\end_inset

.
 This is Hensel's lemma and an estimate.
